sec.p:
A categorical theme emerging early in the analysis of participants’ accounts concerned the apparent changes in the perception of nasopharyngeal mucus which accounted for that physiological sensation being considered deviant, and heralded the onset of transition from order to disorder. There were three changes in evidence:


a putative change in the viscosity of the mucus;


‘it feels thick - I’m sorry to have to put it into words - it’s like a sticky bolus’.

Male, 60 years

a perceived change in the quantity of mucus;


‘I feel it in my throat – it seems to be gathering in my throat all the time and will not go away at all, it doesn’t matter what I try’.

Female, 67 years

a change in the constancy of the sensation;


‘What is the real pain is the constancy of it. There is no let up. At the moment I am quite good. This is good. But it's constant, all the time and I can't imagine what it feels like not to have it now. Although I think it must be really nice [laughs]’.

Female, 49 years

A recurring theme within this ‘social impact’ category was that of embarrassment. Catarrh is generally seen as being undesirable and repulsive – a socially constructed perception – and consequently many patients have become self-conscious in public and concerned about the way in which others perceive them;

‘…if you’re in a crowded place and you’ve got to bring it up, you’re conscious people can hear that and, yeah, it can be very embarrassing. It is for the kids and for my wife’.

Male, 46 years
